What Are Metamorphic Minerals?

  • Definition: Minerals that form under elevated pressure and temperature due to metamorphism.
  • Characteristics:
    • New mineral assemblages due to changes in environmental conditions.
    • Stable only under specific pressure-temperature conditions.
    • Often exhibit foliation or alignment.
  • Examples: Garnet, Kyanite, Sillimanite, Chlorite, Serpentine, Talc.

Formation of Metamorphic Minerals

  • Heat:
    • Promotes recrystallization, resulting in larger and more stable crystals.
  • Pressure:
    • Causes denser mineral structures and alignment of minerals.
  • Fluids:
    • Facilitate chemical reactions, leading to new mineral formations.

Processes of Metamorphic Mineral Formation

  • Recrystallization:
    • Transformation into more stable mineral forms without changing composition.
  • Phase Changes:
    • Example: Andalusite transforming into Sillimanite.
  • Metamorphic Reactions:
    • New mineral assemblages formed by reactions like:
      • Chlorite + Quartz -> Garnet.

Importance of Studying Metamorphic Minerals

  • Indicator of Pressure-Temperature Conditions:
    • Kyanite: High-pressure environments.
    • Andalusite: Low-pressure environments.
  • Geological History:
    • Provides clues to tectonic events and mountain-building processes.
  • Resource Exploration:
    • Economic value in minerals like garnet (abrasive) and graphite.
    • Metamorphic rocks may host mineral deposits.

Common Metamorphic Minerals

  • Garnet: Almandine is typical in medium- to high-grade metamorphism.
  • Kyanite, Sillimanite, Andalusite: Classic indicators of pressure-temperature conditions.
    • Kyanite: High-pressure.
    • Sillimanite: High-temperature.
    • Andalusite: Low-pressure.
  • Chlorite: Found in low-grade metamorphic rocks (e.g., greenschist facies).
  • Serpentine and Talc: Formed by hydration of ultramafic rocks.

Identifying Metamorphic Grade Using Minerals

  • Index Minerals:
    • Chlorite: Low-grade.
    • Biotite: Low- to medium-grade.
    • Garnet: Medium-grade.
    • Kyanite, Sillimanite: High-grade.
  • Metamorphic Facies:
    • Groups of minerals that form under similar conditions:
      • Greenschist Facies: Chlorite, Epidote.
      • Amphibolite Facies: Garnet, Amphibole.
      • Granulite Facies: Pyroxene, Sillimanite.
